## Explanation
Binary search works by repeatedly dividing the search space in half. This is achieved by finding the middle element of the sorted array and comparing it to the target value. If the target value is less than the middle element, the search continues in the left half of the array. If the target value is greater than the middle element, the search continues in the right half. This process is repeated until the target value is found or the search space is empty, indicating that the target value is not in the array. The key to binary search is that it eliminates half of the search space with each comparison, allowing it to find the target value in logarithmic time.

The time complexity of binary search is O(log n), where n is the number of elements in the array. This is because with each comparison, the search space is reduced by half. For example, if you start with an array of 1024 elements, the first comparison eliminates 512 elements, leaving 512 elements to search. The next comparison eliminates 256 elements, leaving 256 elements to search, and so on. This process continues until the target value is found or the search space is empty.

## Example
